01:30.521 --> 01:31.954
Hey, Raj.

01:31.956 --> 01:34.590
Hey, I got you
a little gift.

01:34.592 --> 01:37.159
Oh, that's a lot
of Girl Scout Cookies.

01:37.161 --> 01:39.027
You know me.
I'm from India.

01:39.029 --> 01:41.196
I can't resist children begging.

01:42.299 --> 01:44.733
So, how's it going
with the title to the house?

01:44.735 --> 01:45.667
Great, it's all done.

01:45.669 --> 01:46.735
The lawyer
tracked down my father

01:46.737 --> 01:48.237
and got him to sign it over.

01:48.239 --> 01:49.938
I didn't have to meet him,
I didn't have to talk to him,

01:49.940 --> 01:51.573
I don't even know where he is.

01:51.575 --> 01:54.576
Wow, so you're not curious
at all?

01:54.578 --> 01:55.677
Nope.

01:55.679 --> 01:57.279
Hm. What if he's in prison?

01:57.281 --> 01:59.047
What if he's a spy?

01:59.049 --> 02:01.884
What if he's
in a Beatles cover band?

02:03.053 --> 02:05.220
I'm just saying, if he's got
your nose and haircut,

02:05.222 --> 02:07.389
he'd make a killer Ringo.

02:09.759 --> 02:11.460
Thanks again for
agreeing to do this.

02:11.462 --> 02:13.929
Oh, it's cool; I've never been
on a podcast before.

02:13.931 --> 02:15.898
Well, you picked
a good one to start.

02:15.900 --> 02:17.165
Wil's had lots of great guests.

02:17.167 --> 02:18.834
Jonathan Frakes, Brent Spiner,

02:18.836 --> 02:21.303
Michael Dorn, Gates McFadden...

02:21.305 --> 02:23.338
Those are <i> Star Trek</i> people.

02:23.340 --> 02:24.439
Yes!

02:24.441 --> 02:25.507
I only figured that out

02:25.509 --> 02:27.209
because I've never heard
of any of them.

02:28.279 --> 02:29.611
I deserve that.

02:29.613 --> 02:32.681
I invited you on my show
and I drove here.

02:32.683 --> 02:33.849
Sorry.

02:33.851 --> 02:35.384
Okay, so, this is
basically gonna be

02:35.386 --> 02:36.785
just like a little talk show.

02:36.787 --> 02:38.320
Uh, we're gonna take some calls,

02:38.322 --> 02:40.022
we'll talk about what
it was like on the set

02:40.024 --> 02:41.256
of <i> Serial Ape-ist 2.</i>

02:41.258 --> 02:42.291
It should be really fun.

02:42.293 --> 02:43.759
This is exciting.
Yeah.

02:43.761 --> 02:44.960
So, how many people listen?

02:44.962 --> 02:46.228
Most people download it later,

02:46.230 --> 02:48.297
but usually a few thousand
people listen live.

02:48.299 --> 02:50.265
What?! A few thousand people

02:50.267 --> 02:52.868
listen to you talk
about nerd stuff?

02:54.138 --> 02:56.371
Again, right in the ears,

02:56.373 --> 02:58.307
straight to the feelings.

03:01.245 --> 03:02.978
Can you please pass the salt?

03:02.980 --> 03:04.780
Sure.

03:04.782 --> 03:07.583
It's not like I was invited
to Richard Feynman's house

03:07.585 --> 03:10.018
and have anything better to do.

03:10.020 --> 03:12.955
Is this how the rest
of the night's going to be?

03:12.957 --> 03:15.257
I don't know the future.

03:16.827 --> 03:18.493
Do you think there's a chance

03:18.495 --> 03:20.495
that an asteroid
could hit the Earth,

03:20.497 --> 03:23.966
destroying Feynman's house
and everyone in it?

03:23.968 --> 03:26.134
No, Sheldon.

03:26.136 --> 03:29.471
Then buckle up;
you're in for a cranky night.

03:29.473 --> 03:32.341
According to the codicil
of the Relationship Agreement

03:32.343 --> 03:33.809
which you insisted upon,

03:33.811 --> 03:36.445
we're not allowed to pout
or be moody on date night.

03:36.447 --> 03:40.582
You know I just put that in
because of uterus stuff.

03:41.685 --> 03:44.052
Well, it applies to you, too.

03:44.054 --> 03:46.855
I was afraid you might
bring this up,

03:46.857 --> 03:50.025
so I have a work-around.

03:54.698 --> 03:56.898
There you go.

04:01.939 --> 04:04.706
As far as you're concerned,
I'm smiling.

04:06.076 --> 04:07.976
Although, I must admit,
I'm smiling a little bit

04:07.978 --> 04:10.312
at the moment because
this loophole is so brilliant.

04:12.983 --> 04:14.516
So, Bernadette, have you thought

04:14.518 --> 04:16.785
about how you're going
to redecorate this place?

04:16.786 --> 04:18.754
You know, I'm thinking

04:18.755 --> 04:20.255
ripping up the carpets,

04:20.257 --> 04:21.990
maybe lose the wallpaper,

04:21.992 --> 04:23.325
all new light fixtures...

04:23.327 --> 04:25.160
You know,
if you knocked out this wall,

04:25.162 --> 04:26.895
it would give you an
open floor plan,

04:26.897 --> 04:31.033
and then-- it's a little scary,
but could be fun--

04:31.035 --> 04:34.036
indoor fire pit.

04:34.038 --> 04:35.504
(doorbell rings)

04:35.506 --> 04:37.939
Hey, I grew up
in this house, okay?

04:37.941 --> 04:40.542
No one's knocking anything down.

04:40.544 --> 04:42.177
Okay, okay.

04:42.179 --> 04:43.512
When he's at Comic-Con,

04:43.514 --> 04:46.348
I'm bringing in
a wrecking ball.

04:48.786 --> 04:49.751
Can I help you?

04:49.753 --> 04:52.087
Hi. Are you Howard Wolowitz?

04:52.089 --> 04:53.655
Yes.

04:53.657 --> 04:55.357
Um, this is a little weird,

04:55.359 --> 04:57.492
but a lawyer was trying
to contact my father,

04:57.494 --> 05:00.095
because his name was still
on the title for this house.

05:00.097 --> 05:02.531
W... uh, who's your father?

05:02.533 --> 05:04.399
Sam Wolowitz.

05:04.401 --> 05:05.901
(chuckles)

05:05.903 --> 05:08.370
S-Sam Wolowitz is my father.

05:08.372 --> 05:10.272
I know.

05:10.274 --> 05:14.242
Well, wait, so if we have
the same father...

05:14.244 --> 05:15.277
I mean,

05:15.279 --> 05:16.545
are you saying

05:16.547 --> 05:17.547
you're my half-brother?

05:17.548 --> 05:19.381
I think so.

05:19.383 --> 05:20.649
(chuckles)

05:20.651 --> 05:23.685
Bernadette, weird things
are happening out here!

05:26.657 --> 05:28.990
I think I started to suspect
it was a bad movie

05:28.992 --> 05:32.894
when I looked at the script
and saw the title,

05:32.896 --> 05:35.530
<i>Serial Ape-ist 2:</i>

05:35.532 --> 05:38.533
<i>Monkey See, Monkey Kill.</i>

05:38.535 --> 05:39.868
Uh, spoiler alert:

05:39.870 --> 05:42.571
after the monkey sees, it kills.

05:42.573 --> 05:44.773
Psst.

05:44.775 --> 05:46.508
I've just been handed a note.

05:46.510 --> 05:48.777
I'm going to read it.

05:48.779 --> 05:52.114
"Wil, do you want
more Diet Coke?

05:53.050 --> 05:56.151
Also, we have juice."

05:57.588 --> 06:00.155
I-I didn't want to interrupt.

06:01.258 --> 06:02.791
Uh, that voice you just heard

06:02.793 --> 06:04.626
belongs to Leonard,
Penny's fiancé.

06:04.628 --> 06:06.628
Uh, Leonard, why don't you grab
some headphones and join us?

06:06.630 --> 06:08.163
Really?
Yeah.

06:08.165 --> 06:09.498
(chuckles) Yeah, great.

06:09.500 --> 06:11.333
So, while Leonard
gets set up,

06:11.335 --> 06:12.901
let's take a call.

06:12.903 --> 06:14.469
Hello, caller, you are on

06:14.471 --> 06:16.905
with Penny and Wil
from <i> Serial Ape-ist 2.</i>

06:16.907 --> 06:18.173
WOMAN:
I don't have a question.

06:18.175 --> 06:20.308
I just want to say
I'm a big fan of the movie.

06:20.310 --> 06:21.877
I've seen it, like, ten times.

06:21.879 --> 06:24.312
Okay, well, I'll apologize
for the first time,

06:24.314 --> 06:26.581
but the other nine are on you.

06:26.583 --> 06:28.150
(chuckles)

06:28.152 --> 06:29.518
Thanks a lot, caller.

06:29.520 --> 06:30.920
You know that the movie
actually has

06:30.921 --> 06:32.053
a little bit
of a cult following.

06:32.055 --> 06:33.221
Really?
Yeah.

06:33.223 --> 06:34.556
I was at
a science-fiction convention,

06:34.558 --> 06:37.893
and I saw a woman dressed
as your half-ape character.

06:37.895 --> 06:39.294
Oh, if she was

06:39.296 --> 06:41.463
with an Indian guy dressed
like a banana,

06:41.465 --> 06:44.199
that was just my friends,
Howard and Raj.

06:45.335 --> 06:47.769
All right, it's time
for a very special guest caller,

06:47.771 --> 06:49.371
a friend of mine,
who you probably know

06:49.373 --> 06:51.773
as the director
of such movies as <i> Clerks,</i>

06:51.775 --> 06:53.441
or from podcasts and books

06:53.443 --> 06:55.210
where he often reminds you
that he's the guy

06:55.212 --> 06:56.378
who directed <i> Clerks.</i>

06:56.380 --> 06:57.746
Hello, Kevin Smith.

06:57.748 --> 06:59.681
KEVIN: Hey, man,
yo, is everything okay, Wil?

06:59.683 --> 07:01.750
'Cause it's been,
like, two minutes

07:01.752 --> 07:04.653
and you haven't even brought up
<i>Stand By Me.</i>

07:06.290 --> 07:07.556
Hey, Kevin!

07:07.558 --> 07:09.157
It's really exciting
to talk to you.

07:09.159 --> 07:10.325
It really is.

07:10.327 --> 07:12.360
Oh, you guys are very sweet.
So, Penny, listen,

07:12.362 --> 07:13.695
I saw your movie.

07:13.697 --> 07:15.831
Oh, wow. I wish it was better.

07:15.833 --> 07:16.898
Oh, don't worry about it.

07:16.900 --> 07:18.867
Have you seen some
of Kevin's films?

07:19.970 --> 07:22.637
You're cruisin'
for a beatin', Wheaton.

07:24.174 --> 07:25.907
Anyway, man,
I dug the ape movie, Penny.

07:25.909 --> 07:27.876
And I thought you were, like,
really great in it.

07:27.878 --> 07:29.044
Aw.

07:29.046 --> 07:30.212
You know, I'm in the movie, too.

07:30.214 --> 07:31.813
Yeah, whatever. Penny!

07:31.815 --> 07:35.317
Penny, how come you're not
in more stuff, man?

07:35.319 --> 07:36.518
I'd cast you in a minute.

07:36.520 --> 07:38.420
Seriously?
Oh, yeah, man.

07:38.422 --> 07:40.255
I'm actually in pre-production
on a movie right now.

07:40.257 --> 07:41.356
Way different

07:41.358 --> 07:42.724
than anything I've ever
done before.

07:42.726 --> 07:45.060
It's called <i> Clerks 3.</i>

07:45.062 --> 07:46.595
You should come over

07:46.597 --> 07:48.396
and read for a part.

07:48.398 --> 07:50.599
Oh, my, I would love that.

07:50.601 --> 07:52.000
You have a new job.

07:52.002 --> 07:53.635
Well, maybe I can do both.

07:53.637 --> 07:56.104
I don't think you can do both.

07:56.106 --> 07:58.440
I don't think I asked you.

07:58.442 --> 08:00.275
Yeah, you tell him, Penny.

08:01.578 --> 08:04.679
Stay out of it, Kevin Smith.

08:05.849 --> 08:08.149
Do you think there comes
a point in life

08:08.151 --> 08:11.353
when it stops feeling bad
to be left out of things?

08:11.355 --> 08:12.754
Probably not.

08:12.756 --> 08:14.856
It's an evolutionary advantage

08:14.858 --> 08:17.025
to be included
in group activities.

08:17.027 --> 08:18.593
You know what?

08:18.595 --> 08:20.595
I used to be a fan of evolution,

08:20.597 --> 08:22.330
but I've since evolved,

08:22.332 --> 08:24.900
and now I think it's dumb.

08:26.003 --> 08:27.702
Being left out
is a terrible feeling.

08:27.704 --> 08:29.804
No one understands that
better than I do.

08:29.806 --> 08:31.640
Hey, look at that.

08:31.642 --> 08:34.743
Even in your example,
you're all by yourself.

08:36.513 --> 08:38.746
When there was
a lice epidemic at my school,

08:38.749 --> 08:40.582
everybody got it except me.

08:40.583 --> 08:43.418
I tried to fool everyone
by sprinkling sugar in my hair,

08:43.419 --> 08:46.821
but I just got attacked by bees.

08:47.925 --> 08:49.891
I can just picture
them all right now

08:49.893 --> 08:51.126
at Feynman's house,

08:51.128 --> 08:52.327
probably discussing Schrodinger

08:52.329 --> 08:54.329
and at the same time,

08:54.331 --> 08:56.665
not discussing Schrodinger.

08:56.667 --> 08:58.233
See?

08:58.235 --> 09:02.170
They're missing out
on hilarious jokes like that.

09:02.172 --> 09:04.372
And at the same time, not.

09:06.009 --> 09:08.076
It reminds me of when
my stupid brother and sister

09:08.078 --> 09:09.711
would build forts
in the living room

09:09.713 --> 09:11.313
and wouldn't let me in.

09:11.315 --> 09:13.949
I hated that so much.

09:13.951 --> 09:16.184
You know,

09:16.186 --> 09:17.385
there's nothing I can do

09:17.387 --> 09:19.287
about getting you invited
to the symposium,

09:19.289 --> 09:21.456
but if you wanted...

09:21.458 --> 09:23.358
we could build a fort.

09:24.194 --> 09:26.294
Isn't that a little juvenile?

09:26.296 --> 09:28.463
More juvenile than this?

09:32.035 --> 09:33.168
I'll get the blankets.

09:33.170 --> 09:34.869
You Google how
to have childlike fun.

09:38.275 --> 09:40.075
You know what,
I'm being a bad host.

09:40.077 --> 09:41.276
Let me get some more coffee.

09:41.278 --> 09:43.678
Oh, let me do it, Howard.
No, I got it.

09:46.016 --> 09:47.615
So, Josh, what do you do?

09:47.617 --> 09:49.951
I'm studying oceanography
down in San Diego.

09:49.953 --> 09:52.153
Oh, how nice.

09:55.892 --> 09:58.560
I loved <i> Finding Nemo.</i>

09:59.496 --> 10:00.562
Enough chitchat.

10:00.564 --> 10:02.263
How do we know you are
who you say you are?

10:02.265 --> 10:04.599
Why would I lie?

10:04.601 --> 10:06.901
Okay, you got me there.

10:08.005 --> 10:10.572
You here looking for money?
No.

10:10.574 --> 10:13.041
A kidney, cornea,
piece of his liver?

10:13.043 --> 10:14.409
No.

10:14.411 --> 10:16.277
You're in a Beatles cover band

10:16.279 --> 10:19.547
and you need Howard to replace
your dad as Ringo.

10:20.984 --> 10:22.851
Why don't you help
with the coffee?

10:22.853 --> 10:25.820
Okay, but something
smells fishy.

10:25.822 --> 10:26.855
And not just because

10:26.857 --> 10:28.323
you work around sea animals.

10:29.292 --> 10:30.458
That actually
sounds interesting,

10:30.460 --> 10:32.160
and I'd like
to learn more about it.

10:34.831 --> 10:36.364
Hey, you okay?

10:36.366 --> 10:37.899
Not really.

10:37.901 --> 10:40.502
This guy shows up
out of the blue,

10:40.504 --> 10:42.070
and now I have a brother?

10:42.072 --> 10:45.340
My father has another family?

10:45.342 --> 10:47.175
I get it.

10:47.177 --> 10:48.977
What do you want to do?

10:48.979 --> 10:50.979
I don't know. I...

10:50.981 --> 10:52.814
I'd just like him to go away.

10:52.816 --> 10:54.482
I can't deal with this.

10:54.484 --> 10:56.451
All right, I've got your back.

10:56.453 --> 10:58.620
Thank you. Come on.

11:00.023 --> 11:01.189
And I'd like to point out

11:01.191 --> 11:04.526
this wall just provided
a lot of privacy!

11:06.463 --> 11:08.063
I can't believe
my brother's an astronaut.

11:08.065 --> 11:09.964
That's amazing.  What was it like?
Listen, dude,

11:09.966 --> 11:11.266
it's time for you
to hit the road.

11:11.268 --> 11:13.735
Hey, hey, the young man asked
a good question.

